# DataFlow Engineering Standards

DataFlow is a universal data-movement product. The bar is: **provably better than
Airbyte/Fivetran** — any source to any destination, intelligent schema mapping, and
zero silent data loss. Hold every change to enterprise product quality.

## Code quality & algorithms
- Prefer robust, correct algorithms over clever shortcuts. Handle failures, retries,
  partial progress, concurrency, and multi-instance execution explicitly.
- Never lose or silently drop data. Bad rows are quarantined and surfaced, not dropped.
- Support the full universal type space; coerce with fail-fast preflight, not guesses.
- Back correctness claims with tests/proof artifacts against real services — not "looks fine".

## Architecture & duplication
- No duplication. Reuse the single canonical helper/module; extract shared logic rather
  than copy-paste (services, connectors, adapters, and CSS all share this rule).
- One source of truth per concern (e.g. `tokens.css` for design primitives, one owner
  per shell selector). Extend the canonical layer; do not add `*-v2`/`*-refresh` siblings.
- Keep boundaries clean: connectors, transfer engine, and API routers stay decoupled.

## UI/UX
- Enterprise-grade, HD-quality, responsive on every screen size. Consistent spacing,
  density, and card sizing — no ragged grids.
- One action, one place: never duplicate a control across sidebar, ribbon, and empty state.
- Reuse the design-system primitives in `apps/web/src/components/ui/` (Button, PageShell,
  EmptyState, etc.). Use our own `df2-*` naming — never other companies' class/brand names.

## Verification
- `npm run build` (tsc + vite) must pass clean after frontend changes.
- Trend `pytest` collection errors to zero; run real-service matrices and report actual
  pass/fail counts with proof artifacts before claiming quality.

## Continuous market loop
- Recollect `.cursor/rules/continuous-product-audit.mdc` on every non-trivial change:
  real engine audits, competitor algorithms, catalog honesty, and operator feel-good UX.
